  1. Use rename() to rename the columns and make them easier to use. The new column names should be:
  • country
  • commname
  • ASFIS_sciname
  • ASFIS_spcode
  • ISSCAAP_spgroup
  • ISSCAAP_spgroupname
  • FAO_area
  • unit
fisheries2 <- fisheries %>% 
  dplyr::rename(country = "Country",
                comname = "Common name",
                ASFIS_sciname = "ASFIS species name",
                ASFIS_spcode = "ASFIS species#",
                ISSCAAP_spgroup = "ISSCAAP group#",
                ISSCAAP_spgroupname = "ISSCAAP taxonomic group",
                FAO_area = "FAO major fishing area",
                unit = "Measure")

  1. Are these data tidy? Why or why not, and, how do you know? Use the appropriate pivot function to tidy the data. Remove the NA’s. Put the tidy data frame into a new object fisheries_tidy.
    Data isn’t tidy, the year is a column when it should be a variable
fisheries_tidy <- fisheries2 %>%  
  pivot_longer("1950":"2012",
              names_to = "year",
              values_to = "catch",
              values_drop_na = TRUE)

  1. Which country had the largest overall catch in the year 2000?
fisheries_tidy2 %>%

coastal_fish %>% 
  filter(year == "2010") %>%
  group_by(ASFIS_sciname) %>% 
  summarize(top_coastal_fish = sum(catch, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(top_coastal_fish)) %>% 
  top_n(5)
